  'edu.header.sub':"We don't start from a statistical technique. We start from a business problem. You decide what information you need and which tool solves it.",
  'edu.problems.select.title':'What type of business problem do you want to solve?',
  'edu.problems.select.desc':'Each business problem requires a different type of information — and therefore, a different research technique. Choose the one closest to your situation.',
  'edu.problem0.title':'The problem: how much should it cost?',
  'edu.problem0.p1':'Pricing is one of the hardest decisions in marketing. A price set too low leaves money on the table and raises doubts about quality. A price set too high pushes consumers away before they ever try what you offer.',
  'edu.problem0.p2':'The question isn\'t just "what price maximizes profit?" — it\'s, first and foremost, "what price range does the market consider psychologically reasonable?". That boundary lives in the consumer\'s mind, not on a cost sheet.',
  'edu.problem0.question':'How would you identify that price range without simply asking "how much would you pay?" — a question almost nobody answers honestly?',
  'edu.problem0.solution.title':"The solution you'll learn",
  'edu.problem0.solution.bold':'Price Sensitivity',
  'edu.problem0.solution.desc':'There is a family of <strong>Price Sensitivity</strong> techniques designed exactly for this: instead of asking directly how much someone would pay, respondents are asked to locate different price-perception thresholds. From those answers, the acceptable range emerges mathematically — without the consumer having to "guess" what the researcher wants to hear.',
  'edu.problem0.cta':'See the applied case',
