  'diag.interp.title':'Diagnosis interpretation','diag.noexcl':'No inconsistent responses were found. The data is ready for analysis.',
  'diag.why.title':'Why do we run this diagnosis?',
  'diag.why.text':"In professional market research, no analysis runs without first checking data quality. The consistency rule (too_cheap ≤ cheap ≤ expensive ≤ too_expensive) isn't arbitrary: it reflects the psychological logic that gives the model validity.",
  // Instrument (Diagnosis step — bridge between Pretest and data)
  'edu.instr.title':'This is how this data was collected',
  'edu.instr.desc':'Before checking data quality, let\'s see exactly what each respondent was asked and how the instrument was applied.',
  'edu.instr.howcollected':'How it was collected',
  'edu.instr.howapply':'How to apply this in your own questionnaire',
  'edu.instr.bridge':'This instrument is what collected the data you are about to diagnose next.',
  'edu.instr.vw.tips':'Always keep this fixed order: too cheap → cheap → expensive → too expensive. Use an open price field (the respondent writes the number), never predefined ranges. Show or name the actual product before asking. Do not mention a prior reference price — that anchors responses and invalidates the measurement.',
  'edu.instr.nms.tips':'The 4 base questions come first, same as classic PSM. The 2 intent questions must use the price <em>that same respondent</em> indicated in Q2 and Q3 — not a fixed price for everyone. In the field, the interviewer writes down the price before reading the intent question; on digital platforms, this is handled with conditional logic (piping).',
  'edu.instr.maxdiff.tips':'Works with lists of 5 to 30 items — beyond that range it stops being practical. Each respondent answers several cards (not every possible combination), each with a subset of items. Never replace this with a Likert "importance" scale per item: almost everything ends up rated as important, without distinguishing real priorities — that is precisely the reason MaxDiff exists.',
  'edu.instr.conjoint.tips':'Use between 4 and 6 attributes, with 2 to 5 levels each — more overloads the respondent cognitively. Always include a "None" option on every card, so you don\'t force an unrealistic choice. If the sample allows it, use 2 or more design versions so presentation order doesn\'t bias the results.',
  'edu.instr.turf.tips':'The question can be simple binary ("would you include it? Yes/No"), by threshold (a continuous scale with a cutoff point), or weighted with utilities from a prior MaxDiff or Conjoint study. Choose the format based on what data you already have: if you already ran a MaxDiff, reuse those scores instead of surveying again.',
  'diag.outlier.title':'What are outliers?',
  'diag.outlier.text':'Beyond the consistency rule, we check whether any individual price falls far from the rest using the interquartile range (IQR): values below Q1−1.5×IQR or above Q3+1.5×IQR. These cases aren\'t necessarily "wrong" but can distort averages.',
  'diag.outlier.table.id':'ID','diag.outlier.table.field':'Field','diag.outlier.table.value':'Value','diag.outlier.table.range':'Expected range','diag.outlier.none':'No outliers were detected outside the IQR range.',
